WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.040
 - Okay, so now that we've gotten through the definitions,

00:00:03.040 --> 00:00:05.480
 let's work into some sample code.

00:00:05.480 --> 00:00:06.780
 But hey, look at this.

00:00:06.780 --> 00:00:09.860
 We've got ourselves a cookie cutter and some cookies.

00:00:09.860 --> 00:00:14.080
 So remember that a class is a template.

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:15.760
 It's not the actual thing.

00:00:15.760 --> 00:00:19.920
 An object is an instance of a class.

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:22.700
 So you have to take the class and do something

00:00:22.700 --> 00:00:24.160
 to make the object.

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:26.640
 And actually, you can see here's some other classes.

00:00:26.640 --> 00:00:28.800
 There's clearly a sort of a snowflake class

00:00:28.800 --> 00:00:30.820
 and a gingerbread man class.

00:00:30.820 --> 00:00:32.800
 That's an object, object, object.

00:00:32.800 --> 00:00:35.980
 Somewhere out here, there is a snowflake class

00:00:35.980 --> 00:00:37.700
 and a gingerbread class.

00:00:37.700 --> 00:00:41.480
 But we got a snowman object and a snowman object

00:00:41.480 --> 00:00:42.640
 and a snowman class.

00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:44.720
 So class is the template.

00:00:44.720 --> 00:00:49.560
 Object is the instance.

00:00:49.560 --> 00:00:50.840
 So here's a bit of Python code.

00:00:50.840 --> 00:00:53.680
 So let's take a look at what we got here.

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:56.360
 Class is a new reserved word, kind of like DEF.

00:00:56.360 --> 00:00:57.720
 We have the name of the class.

00:00:57.720 --> 00:00:59.380
 That is a name that we choose.

00:00:59.380 --> 00:01:01.960
 That's the name by which we'll refer to this class

00:01:01.960 --> 00:01:04.100
 for the rest of this program.

00:01:04.100 --> 00:01:06.040
 And it has a colon at the end of it,

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:08.160
 which means it starts an indented block,

00:01:08.160 --> 00:01:10.380
 which ends when we de-indent.

00:01:10.380 --> 00:01:12.440
 Inside the class, there are generally two things.

00:01:12.440 --> 00:01:14.100
 There is some data, and this just looks like

00:01:14.100 --> 00:01:17.220
 an assignment statement in the class, x equals zero.

00:01:17.220 --> 00:01:19.000
 And then there is a DEF.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:20.840
 This looks just like a function.

00:01:20.840 --> 00:01:23.740
 And then it starts with a DEF, has a colon, indents.

00:01:23.740 --> 00:01:26.040
 So that function finishes right there.

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:28.240
 The difference is this is a method

00:01:28.240 --> 00:01:30.360
 because it lives inside of a class.

00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:32.820
 And so there is no function called party.

00:01:32.820 --> 00:01:37.240
 There's a function called party within party animal class.

00:01:37.240 --> 00:01:39.660
 And we'll talk in a second about this self thing.

00:01:39.660 --> 00:01:41.640
 It is the way that inside this code

00:01:41.640 --> 00:01:44.480
 we refer back to that variable.

00:01:44.480 --> 00:01:46.640
 So this is not actually executing any code.

00:01:46.640 --> 00:01:48.820
 It's sort of remembering the template,

00:01:48.820 --> 00:01:51.460
 defining the class party animal.

00:01:51.460 --> 00:01:53.560
 This is what we call constructing.

00:01:53.560 --> 00:01:57.440
 We're constructing using the party animal template or class.

00:01:57.440 --> 00:01:59.280
 We are making a party animal.

00:01:59.280 --> 00:02:03.380
 And then once we make that, we stick it in the variable an.

00:02:03.380 --> 00:02:06.240
 And then we're going to call this party animal,

00:02:06.240 --> 00:02:09.880
 this party method, three times one, two, three.

00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:12.420
 Now this self thing, and we'll take a look at the self.

00:02:12.420 --> 00:02:16.080
 The self ends up being an alias of an.

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:17.720
 And so you can look at this syntax.

00:02:17.720 --> 00:02:20.260
 It's just kind of an equivalent of this syntax.

00:02:20.260 --> 00:02:24.180
 It's calling the party method within the party animal class

00:02:24.180 --> 00:02:27.600
 and passing the instance in as the first parameter.

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:31.480
 And so self ends up being an alias of an

00:02:31.480 --> 00:02:33.000
 each time these are called.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:37.080
 This syntax is a short version of that syntax.

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:39.260
 So if we watch how this executes,

00:02:39.260 --> 00:02:43.300
 it starts up here, it just defines it,

00:02:43.300 --> 00:02:45.920
 and then we construct it.

00:02:45.920 --> 00:02:48.940
 And that's what basically constructing it,

00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:51.520
 we know how to construct it because we look at the class

00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:54.520
 and we make a variable x, we make some code party,

00:02:54.520 --> 00:02:57.240
 and then we construct that, that's what the party animal does,

00:02:57.240 --> 00:02:59.720
 and then we assign that into an.

00:02:59.720 --> 00:03:03.180
 And so an is now pointing at that.

00:03:03.180 --> 00:03:05.740
 Then when we call the party method,

00:03:05.740 --> 00:03:09.280
 that basically takes this an and passes it in

00:03:09.280 --> 00:03:13.600
 as the first parameter, which is used as self.

00:03:13.600 --> 00:03:16.840
 And so self.x, which is what we're doing

00:03:16.840 --> 00:03:18.220
 in this line right here,

00:03:18.220 --> 00:03:21.800
 self.x is a variable, x starts out as zero.

00:03:21.800 --> 00:03:25.720
 X starts out as zero, because when it was constructed,

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:27.820
 it was set to zero, so we're in here,

00:03:27.820 --> 00:03:31.640
 an is an alias of self, and now it looks up self.x,

00:03:31.640 --> 00:03:34.920
 which is zero, adds one to it, and so this becomes one.

00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:37.840
 And then we print so far, so far one.

00:03:37.840 --> 00:03:39.420
 And then the code returns, and it goes down

00:03:39.420 --> 00:03:40.780
 and does it again.

00:03:40.780 --> 00:03:44.100
 And x becomes two, prints out so far two,

00:03:44.100 --> 00:03:46.640
 comes back down, and does the last time,

00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:49.960
 calls it again, self.x is two, add one to it,

00:03:49.960 --> 00:03:52.540
 and stick it back in, so this becomes three,

00:03:52.540 --> 00:03:55.600
 and we print out three, and then the program finishes.

00:03:55.600 --> 00:03:59.440
 And so you can think of this as constructing the object,

00:03:59.440 --> 00:04:03.360
 and then associating it with this an variable.

00:04:03.360 --> 00:04:07.940
 Now, we've created this object, we can play around

00:04:07.940 --> 00:04:10.540
 with things we've played around before with Durantype.

00:04:10.540 --> 00:04:14.700
 We use Durantype to kind of inspect variables and types

00:04:15.900 --> 00:04:20.560
 and objects, so we've been using objects all along.

00:04:20.560 --> 00:04:23.540
 We, this code here says, "Hey, make me an empty list."

00:04:23.540 --> 00:04:25.960
 Well, it turns out that what we're saying is

00:04:25.960 --> 00:04:30.060
 there is already a list class inside of Python,

00:04:30.060 --> 00:04:32.460
 and we're constructing an empty list,

00:04:32.460 --> 00:04:34.740
 and when we get back this empty list,

00:04:34.740 --> 00:04:37.120
 we're assigning that into x.

00:04:37.120 --> 00:04:41.280
 So x, in a sense, contains or points to an empty list.

00:04:41.280 --> 00:04:43.240
 So then we say, "Hey, what is in x?

00:04:43.240 --> 00:04:44.480
 "What kind of thing is x?"

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:47.720
 Well, it's a list, this is a thing, it's a list type.

00:04:47.720 --> 00:04:50.720
 Let's have a list of things in them, and, you know,

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:53.320
 use append, and all the things we've been doing before,

00:04:53.320 --> 00:04:54.480
 they're just objects.

00:04:54.480 --> 00:04:56.760
 And then the dir, if you remember the dir,

00:04:56.760 --> 00:04:59.080
 the dir is the capabilities.

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:00.940
 And there's all these internal capabilities

00:05:00.940 --> 00:05:04.100
 that do things like implement the bracket operator, et cetera,

00:05:04.100 --> 00:05:06.440
 those double underscore ones, we can ignore them,

00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:08.140
 although you can even look them up and figure out

00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:09.720
 what they mean if you feel like it.

00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:13.280
 But the methods that we tend to call are in this class,

00:05:13.280 --> 00:05:18.280
 and so things like x.sort, I've always told you,

00:05:18.280 --> 00:05:21.340
 that is the sort method within the x thing,

00:05:21.340 --> 00:05:24.180
 and the dot operator is the operator that we use

00:05:24.180 --> 00:05:26.360
 to look something up within an object.

00:05:26.360 --> 00:05:29.300
 And so you've been using the syntax all along,

00:05:29.300 --> 00:05:33.500
 x.sort, dictionary.items, all of those are methods

00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:36.000
 within the corresponding class.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:39.040
 If we take a look at this line of code

00:05:39.040 --> 00:05:41.280
 that we've been doing for a very long time,

00:05:41.280 --> 00:05:43.740
 which says, oh, stick hello there into y.

00:05:43.740 --> 00:05:47.760
 It's, if I reword that as more o-o or object-oriented,

00:05:47.760 --> 00:05:50.100
 what this single quote does says,

00:05:50.100 --> 00:05:54.660
 make me a string object and put some text in it,

00:05:54.660 --> 00:05:57.380
 and then when that is done being constructed,

00:05:57.380 --> 00:05:59.840
 stick that into y, right?

00:05:59.840 --> 00:06:03.980
 And so y now points to a string object

00:06:03.980 --> 00:06:06.680
 that's been pre-initialized to the string hello there.

00:06:06.680 --> 00:06:09.560
 Now that's a long way of saying hello there ends up in y,

00:06:09.560 --> 00:06:12.440
 but in o-o terms, we can talk about that.

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:14.620
 If we do a dir of that, we see a whole bunch

00:06:14.620 --> 00:06:18.580
 of internal methods, which have double underscores,

00:06:18.580 --> 00:06:20.800
 and then we see all kinds of methods that we've been using.

00:06:20.800 --> 00:06:23.240
 We've been using methods like upper,

00:06:23.240 --> 00:06:25.560
 we've been using methods like find,

00:06:25.560 --> 00:06:29.140
 we've been using methods like rstrip, right?

00:06:29.140 --> 00:06:32.100
 We've been using these methods.

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:35.340
 So we go on like y.rstrip, parenthesis.

00:06:37.320 --> 00:06:40.780
 Again, that's a method, that's an object,

00:06:40.780 --> 00:06:42.140
 not a class, it's an object,

00:06:42.140 --> 00:06:45.380
 and that is the object lookup operator.

00:06:45.380 --> 00:06:50.060
 Now if we do the same thing to code that we've built,

00:06:50.060 --> 00:06:51.360
 or a class that we've built,

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:54.120
 so now we have a party animal class,

00:06:54.120 --> 00:06:56.780
 remember this up to here is just definition,

00:06:56.780 --> 00:06:59.680
 now we construct it and we store it in an,

00:06:59.680 --> 00:07:01.520
 so an is a variable that contains

00:07:01.520 --> 00:07:03.940
 an object of type party animal.

00:07:03.940 --> 00:07:07.340
 We ask it what type it is, and it prints out here,

00:07:07.340 --> 00:07:11.820
 it says this is a class, and it's main_party_animal,

00:07:11.820 --> 00:07:14.700
 and this whole thing here is the underscore main,

00:07:14.700 --> 00:07:16.980
 it's scoped_main, but you can see

00:07:16.980 --> 00:07:19.140
 that you have made a new type.

00:07:19.140 --> 00:07:22.180
 You built a type by using this class keyword.

00:07:22.180 --> 00:07:25.480
 And then we use the dir, remember dir looks for capabilities,

00:07:25.480 --> 00:07:27.560
 and again, you will see,

00:07:27.560 --> 00:07:30.980
 you'll see a whole bunch of underscore things,

00:07:30.980 --> 00:07:32.780
 they have meaning, you can look them up,

00:07:32.780 --> 00:07:34.280
 but eventually you'll see the two things

00:07:34.280 --> 00:07:36.720
 that you've put in it, one is the method party,

00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:39.860
 and the other is the attribute, or field X.

00:07:39.860 --> 00:07:44.460
 And again, these are the things that you can say an.x,

00:07:44.460 --> 00:07:48.620
 or an.party, 'cause this dot is the object operator,

00:07:48.620 --> 00:07:52.920
 the object lookup operator that says,

00:07:52.920 --> 00:07:55.600
 lookup in the object and the thing X,

00:07:55.600 --> 00:07:59.760
 or lookup in the object and the thing party, okay?

00:08:01.740 --> 00:08:03.200
 So up next, we'll talk a little bit

00:08:03.200 --> 00:08:06.040
 about how objects are created and destroyed.

00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:09.040
 We also call that object lifecycle.

